{"title_page": "Ariadne (archive)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n'''Ariadne''' is an archive center for information on women hosted by the [[Austrian National Library]] in Vienna. Ariadne was founded by [[Christa Bittermann-Wille]] and [[Helga Hofmann-Weinberger]] in 1992 with the aim of facilitating study on [[gender studies|gender]] and [[women's studies|women]]. It provides a digital interface for locating information by and about women. The center is located at Josefsplatz 1, A-1015 in [[Vienna]], which is the address of the Austrian National Library, and does not offer a separate facility for women's research.\n\n==History==\nBetween 1986 and 1987, [[Christa Bittermann-Wille]] and Andrea Fennesz, conducted a feasibility study in coordination with the Austrian Ministry of Science, on the creation of an archive and information center for women.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=207}} The rise of [[Second-wave feminism]] and the establishment of new feminist research within academia had brought forward the dissatisfaction with the availability and depth of coverage of women's topics in traditional library collections.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|pp=207\u2013209}} Similar organizations abroad, like the [[Atria Institute on gender equality and women's history|Atria Institute]] in [[Amsterdam]] and the [[FrauenMediaTurm]] in [[Cologne]], were studied.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=207}} One of the biggest questions posed in the study was whether state intervention in the collection of women's documents would be accepted by institutions which already had begun women's collections as an imposition of [[patriarchy]]. It was proposed that such a collection be housed under the auspices of the [[Austrian National Library]], as it was the largest scientific library in the country.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=209}} In 1991, Bittermann-Wille began a series of consultations with interested stakeholders to determine whether the project would be accepted by other women's libraries, archives and their curators and patrons. The time period coincided with the birth of the digital age and archivists and librarians saw potential in the proposal, as long as the state did not dictate what materials should be collected and retained.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|pp=209\u2013210}}\n\n==Organization==\nAriadne was founded by Bittermann-Wille and [[Helga Hofmann-Weinberger]] in 1992 with the aim of facilitating study on [[gender studies|gender]] and [[women's studies|women]].{{sfn|\u00d6sterreichische Nationalbibliothek|2019}} The facility provides a digital interface for locating information by and about women.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|p=8}} Because traditional categorization of women's materials often obscured relevant works, produced limited search results, or were did not adequately represent women's works, new types of categorization were developed.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=210}} Through networks with women's study institutions, historians and literary writers, Ariadne began to collect historic records to make them available for study and research{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|pp=210\u2013211}} with the goal of restoring the cultural memory and women's visibility in the historical record.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=212}}\n\nAriadne functions as a department of the Austrian National Library and does not have a designated reading room, nor are the works kept separately shelved from the library's other collections.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=213}} The collections began being digitized and offered through a web portal in 2000 to broaden accessibility.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=211}} A limitation on the material is that it is mostly available in the German language.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|p=8}} Another limitation is that as of 2006, the archive of the [[umbrella organization]] ''{{ill|Bund \u00d6sterreichischer Frauenvereine|de}}'' (Federation of Austrian Women's Organizations), possibly one of the largest archives of documents from the ''[[fin de si\u00e8cle]]'' in Austria have remained private and inaccessible to BOF members, academics, and Ariadne personnel.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|pp=13\u201314}}\n\n==Collections and productions==\nThe collections of Ariadne contain works by and about women, their works, and the movements they were involved in as found in literature and other publications, as well as in gender and feminist studies. Though the focus is primarily on Austrian women, the collection also contains material on women from other countries.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|p=17}}\n\nThe collection on the early women's movement in Austria is titled ''Frauen in Bewegung'' (Women in Motion).{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=210}} Digitization of women's journals, magazines, and newspapers from the time of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] (1282\u20131806) is an on-going process.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=212}} Many of the journals provide information on notable historic figures, but also illuminate those unknown activists and the associations and activities they were involved with.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=211}}\n\nCollaborative works have been sponsored by Ariadne and resulted in the production of ''BiographiA'', ''KolloquiA'', and ''ThesaurA'', among others.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=210}} ''ThesaurA'' was created in 1997 to provide a gendered language guide and inclusive reference to be used by archives and libraries to facilitate location of materials. The aim was not simply to make both sexes visible, rather than relying on a customary \"default is male\" categorization, but to also make gender less obscure in searching for materials using collective nouns, such as ''workers'' or ''movement''.{{sfn|BARTOC|2019}} ''KolloquiA'' was published in 2001 and presents an inventory of available materials, research facilities and teaching references for women's information in Austria. Designed for both feminist experts and information science professionals, the material is designed to facilitate gender research.{{sfn|Jank|2002|pp=201\u2013203}}\n\nThough the ''BiographiA'' project began in 1998, the research required to compile the 6,500 biographies in the 4-volume publication delayed publication until 2015. The [[Encyclopedic dictionary|lexicon]] provides biographical sketches of Austrian women from the Roman period to the 21st century. In addition to the published volumes, Ariadne hosts an on-line database of around 20,000 biographies.{{sfn|Hemecker|\u00d6sterle|2016|p=573}}\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite thesis |ref=harv |last1=Broussard |first1=Sarah Kemeny |title=An Introduction to the Leaders and Journals of the ''Allgemeine \u00d6sterreichische Frauenverein'' (A\u00d6FV), or General Austrian Women's Organization: 1893\u20131910 |url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1005&context=studentpub_uht |type=Undergraduate Honors Thesis |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]] |location=Provo, Utah |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517060415/https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1005&context=studentpub_uht |archivedate=17 May 2018 |date=March 2006}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Hemecker |first1=Wilhelm |last2=\u00d6sterle |first2=David |title=Biography in Austria, a Selection: The Year in Austria |journal=[[Biography (journal)|Biography]] |date=Fall 2016 |volume=39 |issue=4 |pages=573\u2013577 |doi=10.1353/bio.2016.0067 |publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press]] |location=Honolulu, Hawaii |issn=0162-4962}}{{subscription needed|via=[[Project MUSE]]}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Jammernegg |first1=Lydia |title=\u00dcber 20 Jahre Ariadne. Die Frauenspezifische Information und Dokumentation an der \u00d6sterreichischen Nationalbibliothek |journal=V\u00d6B-Mitteilungen |date=2016 |volume=69 |issue=2 |pages=206\u2013220 |url=http://eprints.rclis.org/30481/1/1627-5442-1_Jammernegg_Ueber_20_Jahre_Ariadne.pdf |accessdate=11 November 2019 |trans-title=Over 20 Years of Ariadne: Women-Specific Information and Documentation at the Austrian National Library |publisher=Association of Austrian Librarians & Librarians |location=Graz, Austria |language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111164242/http://eprints.rclis.org/30481/1/1627-5442-1_Jammernegg_Ueber_20_Jahre_Ariadne.pdf |archivedate=11 November 2019 |issn=1022-2588|doi=10.31263/voebm.v69i2.1627 }}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Jank |first1=Dagmar |title=Rezensionent: KolloquiA. Frauenbezogene/feministische Dokumentation und Informationsarbeit in \u00d6sterreich. Lehr- und Forschungsmaterialien. Hrsg. von frida \u2013Verein zur F\u00f6rderung und Vernetzung frauenspezifischer Informations- und Dokumentationseinrichtungen in \u00d6sterreich. Wien: Bundesministerium f\u00fcr Bildung, Wissenschaft und Kultur, 2001. 607 S. (Materialien zur F\u00f6rderung von Frauen in der Wissenschaft; 11) \u2013 ISBN 3-85224-059-X |journal=Bibliothek Forschung und Praxis |date=2002 |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=201\u2013203 |url=https://www.degruyter.com/downloadpdf/j/bfup.2002.26.issue-2/bfup.2002.201/bfup.2002.201.pdf |accessdate=11 November 2019 |trans-title=Review: 'Colloquia'. Women's/Feminist Documentation and Informational Works in Austria. Teaching and Research Materials. Edited by Frida \u2013 Association for the Promotion and Networking of Women's Information and Documentation in Austria. Vienna: Federal Ministry of Education, Science and Culture, 2001. 607 p. Materials for the Advancement of Women in Science; 11) \u2013 ISBN 3-85224-059-X |publisher=[[De Gruyter]] |location=Berlin, Germany |language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111213725/https://www.degruyter.com/downloadpdf/j/bfup.2002.26.issue-2/bfup.2002.201/bfup.2002.201.pdf |archivedate=11 November 2019 |issn=1865-7648}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|\u00d6sterreichische Nationalbibliothek|2019}} |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Guide through the maze of female and gender-specific knowledge |url=https://www.onb.ac.at/en/research/ariadne/abou