brought forward the dissatisfaction with the availability and depth of coverage of women's topics in traditional library collections.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|pp=207\u2013209}} Similar organizations abroad, like the [[Atria Institute on gender equality and women's history|Atria Institute]] in [[Amsterdam]] and the [[FrauenMediaTurm]] in [[Cologne]], were studied.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=207}} One of the biggest questions posed in the study was whether state intervention in the collection of women's documents would be accepted by institutions which already had begun women's collections as an imposition of [[patriarchy]]. It was proposed that such a collection be housed under the auspices of the [[Austrian National Library]], as it was the largest scientific library in the country.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=209}} In 1991, Bittermann-Wille began a series of consultations with interested stakeholders to determine whether the project would be accepted by other women's libraries, archives and their curators and patrons. The time period coincided with the birth of the digital age and archivists and librarians saw potential in the proposal, as long as the state did not dictate what materials should be collected and retained.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|pp=209\u2013210}}\n\n==Organization==\nAriadne was founded by Bittermann-Wille and [[Helga Hofmann-Weinberger]] in 1992 with the aim of facilitating study on [[gender studies|gender]] and [[women's studies|women]].{{sfn|\u00d6sterreichische Nationalbibliothek|2019}} The facility provides a digital interface for locating information by and about women.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|p=8}} Because traditional categorization of women's materials often obscured relevant works, produced limited search results, or were did not adequately represent women's works, new types of categorization were developed.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=210}} Through networks with women's study institutions, historians and literary writers, Ariadne began to collect historic records to make them available for study and research{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|pp=210\u2013211}} with the goal of restoring the cultural memory and women's visibilty in the historical record.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=212}} \n\nAriadne functions as a department of the Austrian National Library and does not have a designated reading room, nor are the works kept separately shelved from the library's other collections.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=213}} The collections began being digitized and offered through a web portal in 2000 to broaden accessibility.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=211}} A limitation on the material is that it is mostly available in the German language.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|p=8}} Another limitation is that as of 2006, the archive of the [[umbrella organization]] ''{{ill|Bund \u00d6sterreichischer Frauenvereine|de}}'' (Federation of Austrian Women's Organizations), possibly one of the largest archives of documents from the ''[[fin de si\u00e8cle]]'' in Austria have remained private and inaccessible to BOF members, academics, and Ariadne personnel.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|pp=13\u201314}}\n\n==Collections and productions==\nThe collections of Ariadne contain works by and about women, their works, and the movements they were involved in as found in literature and other publications, as well as in gender and feminist studies. Though the focus is primarily on Austrian women, the collection also contains material on women from other countries.{{sfn|Broussard|2006|p=17}} \n\nThe collection on the early women's movement in Austria is titled ''Frauen in Bewegung'' (Women in Motion).{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=210}} Digitization of women's journals, magazines, and newspapers from the time of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] (1282\u20131806) is an on-going process.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=212}} Many of the journals provide information on notable historic figures, but also illuminate those unknown activists and the associations and activities they were involved with.{{sfn|Jammernegg|2016|p=211}}\n\nCollab